<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>BF-3 Sample Outcomes</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers difference quotients and piecewise functions. Given a function <m>f(x)</m>, 
      you should be able to compute a difference quotient, such as: <m>\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}</m> and simplify 
      it. Given a piecewise function, you should be able to find the domain, the boundary points, the intercepts, 
      and sketch the graph. You should be able to write out complete steps to solve these types of problems 
      by hand, without the use of a calculator.
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
        <li><p>Basics of Graphing: Give a graph with appropriate scales and labels. The curves should have the 
          correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>Difference Quotients: Evaluate the functions and simplify difference quotients for 
        various functions.</p></li>
      <li><p>Piecewise Functions: Evaluate piecewise functions at specific points and graph them. be able 
        to give a simplified domain and state specific points on the graph.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <statement><p>
          Given the function <m>f(x)=\frac{x}{x-3}</m>. Find and simplify the 
          difference quotient <m>\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}</m>.
      </p></statement>
      <hint><p>Start by evaluating both <m>f(x+h)</m> and <m>f(x)</m> separately. 
        Then simplify the resulting expression.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}=\frac{3}{(x+h-3)(x-3)}</m></p></answer>
      <solution><p>To begin we will start by evaluating each function: 
        <m>f(x+h)=\frac{x+h}{x+h-3}</m> and <m>f(x)=\frac{x}{x-3}</m>. Putting 
        these together and simplify the expression. 
        <md><mrow>\begin{aligned}\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} =&amp; \frac{\frac{x+h}{x+h-3}-\frac{x}{x-3}}{h}</mrow>
          <mrow> =&amp; \frac{\frac{(x+h)(x-3)-x(x+h-3)}{(x+h-3)(x-3)}}{h}</mrow>
          <mrow> =&amp; \frac{\frac{3h}{(x+h-3)(x-3)}}{h}</mrow>
          <mrow> =&amp; \frac{3}{(x+h-3)(x-3)}\end{aligned}</mrow></md></p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <statement><p>
          Given the function <m>f(x)=4x^2-5x</m>. Find and simplify the 
          difference quotient <m>\frac{f(a)-f(3)}{a-3}</m>.
      </p></statement>
      <hint><p>Start by evaluating both <m>f(a)</m> and <m>f(3)</m> separately. 
        Then simplify the resulting expression.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>\frac{f(a)-f(3)}{a-3}=4a+7</m></p></answer>
      <solution><p>To begin we will start by evaluating each function: 
        <m>f(a)=4a^2-5a</m> and <m>f(3)=4(3)^2-5(3)=36-15=21</m>. Putting 
        these together and simplify the expression. 
        <md><mrow>\begin{aligned}\frac{f(a)-f(3)}{a-3} =&amp;\frac{4a^2-5a-21}{a-3}</mrow>
          <mrow> =&amp; \frac{(4a+7)(a-3)}{a-3}</mrow>
          <mrow> =&amp; 4a+7\end{aligned}</mrow></md></p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <statement><p>
        Graph the function <me>f(x)=\begin{cases}5-3x \text{ }&amp; 
          \text{ }x\le -1\\x^2+1 \text{ }&amp; \text{ } -1 \lt x\lt 2\\ 
          3x+2 \text{ }&amp; \text{ } x\ge 2\end{cases}</me>
        Also state the domain, boundary points and intercepts.
      </p></statement>
      <hint><p>Start by finding the boundary points and the domain, then graph and find the intercepts.</p></hint>
      <answer><p>Domain: <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>, Boundary points: <m>(-1, 8), (-1,2), (2,5)</m> and <m>(2, 8)</m>, 
        Intercepts: <m>(0, 1)</m></p>
      <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-bf3-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <coordinates bbox="(-15,-15,15,15)">
                    <definition>f(x)=x^2+1</definition>
                    <grid spacings="((-15,3,15),(-15,3,15))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="f" domain="(-1,2)"/>
                    <line endpoints="((-1,8),(-3,14))" stroke="blue" arrows="1"></line>
                    <line endpoints="((2,8),(4,14))" stroke="blue" arrows="1"></line>
                    <point p="(-1,8)"  fill="blue" alignment="sw">bp</point>
                    <point p="(-1,2)" fill="white" alignment="s">bp</point>
                    <point p="(2,5)" fill="white" alignment="e">bp</point>
                    <point p="(2,8)" fill="blue" alignment="e">bp</point>
                    <point p="(0,1)" fill="blue" alignment="se">int</point>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                                text="The graph of the piecewise function has three distinct pieces, two linear 
                                pieces on the ends and a quadratic piece in the middle. As x increases from negative infinity, 
                                the function follows the linear piece y=5-3x on the left up to the boundary point at (-1, 8), then transitions 
                                to the quadratic piece y=x^2+1 in the middle starting at (-1, 2) and ending at (2, 5), and finally from the point 
                                (2, 8) follows the linear piece y=3x+2 on the right.">
                      </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image></answer>
      <solution><p>To graph the function, we will consider each piece separately:
        <ul>
          <li>For <m>x \le -1</m>, the function is <m>f(x) = 5 - 3x</m>. This is a linear function 
            with a slope of <m>-3</m> and a point at <m>(-1,8)</m>.</li>
          <li>For <m>-1 \lt x \lt 2</m>, the function is <m>f(x) = x^2 + 1</m>. This is a parabola 
            opening upwards with a vertex at <m>(0, 1)</m> and points at <m>(-1, 2)</m> and <m>(2, 5)</m>.</li>
          <li>For <m>x \ge 2</m>, the function is <m>f(x) = 3x + 2</m>. This is a linear 
            function with a slope of <m>3</m> and a point at <m>(2, 8)</m>.</li>
        </ul>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet> 
